%description:
Regression/feature test for Workstream F3 Phase 5 (RFC 7552 subset): proves that LDP
itself -- not static XML configuration -- discovers peers, forms sessions, and
DYNAMICALLY advertises and learns an IPv6 FEC (a Label Mapping message whose FEC TLV
carries an IPv6 prefix, Address Family = 2 on the wire), and that real end-to-end IPv6
packet delivery happens over the resulting LDP-signaled LSP using the dynamically
learned labels (no static <fectable>/<libtable> XML anywhere in this test).

Topology, all point-to-point ppp links (mirrors the shape of the existing
examples/mpls/ldp/LDPTEST network and of mpls_ipv6_static_lsp.test, scaled down to one
core transit hop):

  hostA -- LSR1 (ingress) -- LSR2 (core transit) -- LSR3 (egress) -- hostB

- hostA/hostB: plain ~StandardHost, hasIpv6 = true.
- LSR1/LSR2/LSR3: ~LdpMplsRouter (~MplsRouterBase + real ~Ldp signaling, no static XML
  FEC/LIB configuration anywhere), each with hasIpv6 = true. Unlike
  mpls_ipv6_static_lsp.test's transit LSR (which has NO IPv6 awareness at all, since a
  purely static classifier never needs one), LSR2 here DOES need hasIpv6 = true and an
  IPv6 route to hostB's prefix in its own Ipv6RoutingTable: DU-mode LDP only advertises/
  accepts bindings for FECs the local router itself recognizes (Ldp::rebuildFecList()
  populates fecList from the LOCAL routing table; Ldp::processLABEL_MAPPING ignores a
  mapping for a FEC it doesn't recognize) -- exactly mirroring how a real dynamic IPv4
  LDP LSP depends on IGP-learned routes at every transit hop, not just the edges.
- IPv4 core addressing is fully static (.rt files, mirrors LDPTEST/static_lsp.test's
  style): this is what LDP's own Hello/TCP session establishment runs over -- LDP
  peering/transport stays IPv4-only in this model (RFC 7552's design: a session's
  transport address family is independent of which FEC families it advertises).
- IPv6 addressing/routing is fully AUTOMATIC (~Ipv6NetworkConfigurator's default
  wildcard address-assignment + Dijkstra route computation), applied across the WHOLE
  chain hostA..hostB, INCLUDING the core router-to-router links -- not just the edges.
  This is the deliberate difference from mpls_ipv6_static_lsp.test's single-link manual
  config: it gives every router along the path (including transit LSR2) a real IPv6
  route to hostB's prefix with a real next-hop gateway address, so
  Ldp::rebuildFecList()'s IPv6 loop actually has something to turn into a FEC on every
  hop. hostA/hostB's own addresses are pinned to fixed literals (2001:db8:a::1,
  2001:db8:b::1) so the traffic-generator config below can target a literal (not a
  symbolic hostname -- hostB also carries a dormant IPv4 address, for ~Ted, so a bare
  hostname lookup could ambiguously resolve to either family).

Design note on Fec::nextHop resolution for an IPv6 route (see Ldp::rebuildFecList()):
Fec::nextHop stays an Ipv4Address LDP peer identifier even for an IPv6 FEC (LDP peering
is IPv4-only). It is resolved via Ldp::findIpv4NextHopForInterface(): the IPv4 routing
table's own directly-connected-neighbor route through the same local interface the IPv6
route egresses on -- e.g. LSR1's route to hostB's prefix egresses via its LSR2-facing
interface, and the IPv4 table's route through that same interface names LSR2's real
address, so nextHop becomes LSR2's address (an ordinary transit FEC; whether LSR2 is
CURRENTLY an operational LDP peer is, correctly, decided later and afresh every time via
findPeerSocket(), exactly like the IPv4 loop's own nextHop). For LSR3's OWN route to
hostB's prefix (the directly-connected hostB-facing interface), the IPv4 table's route
through that SAME interface names hostB's own (dormant, Ted-only) IPv4 address --
findPeerSocket() will (correctly, always) report that hostB is not an LDP peer, so
duAdvertiseToPeer() takes the ER=true ("we are egress") branch. This is deliberately
NOT resolved via myPeers (a peer's live Hello adjacency): rebuildFecList() runs once at
INITSTAGE_ROUTING_PROTOCOLS, before ANY Hello has been sent, so myPeers is always empty
at that point -- a myPeers-based lookup would incorrectly treat EVERY IPv6 route as
egress (not just the genuinely-egress one), and nothing would ever revisit that
decision afterwards (this model's IPv6 routing table never changes once configured, so
no further routeAdded/routeDeleted signal re-triggers rebuildFecList() later once
sessions actually come up). The IPv4-routing-table correlation is stable regardless of
session timing, which is what makes LSR3 reliably recognize itself as egress for
hostB's prefix -- without it, the LSP could never complete end to end.

Asserted, in order:
  1. all three LDP sessions establish over TCP;
  2. LSR3 sends (and LSR2 receives) a Label Mapping whose FEC TLV carries hostB's IPv6
     prefix -- proves RFC 7552 IPv6 FEC advertisement actually happened over the wire,
     not just in memory;
  3. the data plane is label-switched using the dynamically learned label, for hostA's
     IPv6 traffic to hostB: LSR1 (ingress) pushes it, and LSR2 (penultimate hop) pops it
     rather than swapping, per penultimate-hop-popping/PHP (advertiseImplicitNull, on by
     default -- see the design note above);
  4. hostB actually receives the IPv6 UDP traffic;
  5. standard undisposed-object postrun guard.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LdpIpv6FecTest.ned

import inet.networklayer.configurator.ipv6.Ipv6NetworkConfigurator;
import inet.node.inet.StandardHost;
import inet.node.mpls.LdpMplsRouter;

//
// hostA -- LSR1 (ingress) -- LSR2 (core transit) -- LSR3 (egress) -- hostB. Real LDP
// signaling throughout (no static FEC/LIB XML); IPv6 addressing/routing is fully
// automatic (~Ipv6NetworkConfigurator), including across the core, so every LDP router
// -- not just the edges -- has its own IPv6 route to hostB's prefix.
//
network LdpIpv6FecTest
{
    submodules:
        hostA: StandardHost {
            hasIpv6 = true;
            @display("p=100,100");
        }
        LSR1: LdpMplsRouter {
            hasIpv6 = true;
            @display("p=250,100");
        }
        LSR2: LdpMplsRouter {
            hasIpv6 = true;
            @display("p=400,100");
        }
        LSR3: LdpMplsRouter {
            hasIpv6 = true;
            @display("p=550,100");
        }
        hostB: StandardHost {
            hasIpv6 = true;
            @display("p=700,100");
        }
        configurator: Ipv6NetworkConfigurator {
            @display("p=400,300");
        }
    connections:
        hostA.pppg++ <--> { delay = 10ms; datarate = 1Mbps; } <--> LSR1.pppg++;
        LSR1.pppg++ <--> { delay = 10ms; datarate = 1Mbps; } <--> LSR2.pppg++;
        LSR2.pppg++ <--> { delay = 10ms; datarate = 1Mbps; } <--> LSR3.pppg++;
        LSR3.pppg++ <--> { delay = 10ms; datarate = 1Mbps; } <--> hostB.pppg++;
}

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: hostA.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.0.1	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.0.2	*		255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp0
default:	10.0.0.2	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR1.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.0.2	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.1.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 2
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.0.1	10.0.0.1	255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp0
10.0.1.2	10.0.1.2	255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp1

224.0.0.0	*		255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR2.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.1.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 2
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.2.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 2
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.1.1	10.0.1.1	255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp0
10.0.2.2	10.0.2.2	255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp1

224.0.0.0	*		255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*		255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR3.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.2.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 2
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.3.1	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.2.1	10.0.2.1	255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp0
10.0.3.2	10.0.3.2	255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp1

224.0.0.0	*		255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: hostB.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.3.2	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.3.1	*		255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp0
default:	10.0.3.1	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%inifile: test.ini

[General]
ned-path = .;../../../../src
network = LdpIpv6FecTest
sim-time-limit = 6s
total-stack = 64MiB
record-vector-results = false
cmdenv-express-mode = false
**.cmdenv-log-level = "info"
output-scalar-file = "${resultdir}/${configname}-#${runnumber}.sca"

**.hostA.numApps = 1
**.hostA.app[0].typename = "UdpBasicApp"
**.hostA.app[0].localPort = 100
**.hostA.app[0].destPort = 100
**.hostA.app[0].messageLength = 128 bytes
**.hostA.app[0].sendInterval = 0.1s
# start well after LDP sessions/labels have had time to converge (see the LSR*.holdTime/
# helloInterval settings below, which shorten the discovery/session timers for this test)
**.hostA.app[0].startTime = 3s
# a literal IPv6 address (not the symbolic hostname "hostB"): hostB also carries a
# dormant (Ted-only) IPv4 address, so resolving a bare hostname could pick either family
**.hostA.app[0].destAddresses = "2001:db8:b::1"

**.hostB.numApps = 1
**.hostB.app[0].typename = "UdpSink"
**.hostB.app[0].localPort = 100

# IPv4 core addressing/routing is entirely static (.rt files); no Ipv4NetworkConfigurator
# is present in this network, so each node's Ipv4NodeConfigurator must be told not to
# look for one.
**.ipv4.configurator.networkConfiguratorModule = ""
**.hostA.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "hostA.rt"
**.LSR1.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR1.rt"
**.LSR2.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR2.rt"
**.LSR3.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR3.rt"
**.hostB.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "hostB.rt"

# IPv6 addressing/routing is fully automatic, across the WHOLE chain including the core
# router-to-router links -- this is what gives LSR2 (transit) its own IPv6 route to
# hostB's prefix (see this file's %description). hostA/hostB get pinned literal
# addresses so the traffic-generator config above can target one deterministically.
*.configurator.config = xml("<config>\
    <interface hosts='hostA' names='ppp0' address='2001:db8:a::1' prefix='2001:db8:a::/64'/>\
    <interface hosts='LSR1' names='ppp0' prefix='2001:db8:a::/64'/>\
    <interface hosts='LSR3' names='ppp1' prefix='2001:db8:b::/64'/>\
    <interface hosts='hostB' names='ppp0' address='2001:db8:b::1' prefix='2001:db8:b::/64'/>\
    <interface hosts='**' prefix='2001:db8:x:x::/64'/>\
    </config>")
**.ipv6.configurator.networkConfiguratorModule = "configurator"
**.neighbourDiscovery.dupAddrDetectTransmits = 0

**.ppp[*].queue.typename = "DropTailQueue"
**.ppp[*].queue.packetCapacity = 10

# shorten LDP discovery/session timers so sessions and labels have converged well before
# hostA.app[0]'s 3s startTime
**.LSR*.holdTime = 2s
**.LSR*.helloInterval = 0.5s

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# 1. all three LDP sessions establish over TCP
%contains: stdout
TCP connection established with peer
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# 2. LSR3 (egress) sends a Label Mapping whose FEC TLV is hostB's IPv6 prefix specifically
%# (not just any Label Mapping) -- proves RFC 7552 IPv6 FEC advertisement (Address Family
%# = 2 on the wire, see LdpPacketSerializer::serializeFecTlv) actually happened, not just
%# something coincidental in memory
%contains: stdout
DU: advertising unsolicited Label Mapping (egress) label=3 for fec addr=2001:db8:b:: length=64
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# ...and a downstream peer (LSR2) received it, dynamically learning the same FEC
%contains: stdout
Label mapping label=3 received for fec=addr=2001:db8:b::  length=64
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# 3. the data plane is label-switched using the dynamically learned label: LSR1 (ingress)
%# pushes it (PHP means LSR2, the penultimate hop, pops rather than swaps -- see
%# %description -- so PUSH/POP is the complete, correct label-operation set here)
%contains: stdout
doStackOps: {PUSH
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains: stdout
doStackOps: {POP}
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# 4. hostB actually receives the IPv6 UDP traffic sent by hostA over the LDP-signaled LSP
%postrun-command: grep "packetReceived:count" results/General-#0.sca | awk '$NF > 0 { print "DELIVERED", $0 }' > delivered.out
%contains: delivered.out
DELIVERED
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
